description:
Mark’s big focus is on Jesus as the man of power. So Mark sets the scene for the Jesus’ appearance by the way John the Baptist introduces him. Take a look…

And so John the Baptist appeared in the wilderness, preaching a baptism of repentance for the forgiveness of sins. The whole Judean countryside and all the people of Jerusalem went out to him. Confessing their sins, they were baptized by him in the Jordan River. John wore clothing made of camel’s hair, with a leather belt around his waist, and he ate locusts and wild honey. And this was his message: “After me comes the one more powerful than I, the straps of whose sandals I am not worthy to stoop down and untie. I baptize you with water, but he will baptize you with the Holy Spirit.” – Mark 1:4–8

Mark introduces John the Baptist as a man of incredible power. The Baptist’s message, paraphrased, is, “If you think I’m powerful, just wait till you experience the power of the one who is coming after me! I am nothing compared to him.”

The Jewish people loved to get themselves baptised in water, sometimes many times a day. But the John the Baptist tells them that the one who is coming will baptise them, not with water, but with the Holy Spirit, the true source of power.

In our culture, like in Jesus’ day, we tend to show our power and status through external things, like what we wear, eating at fancy restaurants, and by the stuff we have. But Mark points out that John, this great man of power, dressed and ate very differently to what was expected in his own culture.

He’s pointing out that true power doesn’t come from the external trappings, but from being faithful to God’s call on your life. Take some time to reflect on how you relate to the idea of power in your life. Do you rely on the externals? Or do you rely on God alone?
